RESULTS: Total 218 (87%) younger patients and 33 (13%) older patients who 
underwent ACDF were analyzed. Both the groups demonstrated a significant 
improvement in PROs 2-year following surgery. The older patients had a lower 
mean cumulative gain in QALYs compared to younger patients at 1 year (0.141 vs. 
0.28, P = 0.05) and 2 years (0.211 vs. 0.424, P = 0.04). There was no 
significant difference in the mean total 2-year cost between older [$21,041 (95% 
CI $18,466-$23,616)] and younger [$22,669 (95% CI $$21,259-$24,079)] patients 
(P = 0.27). Two-year cost per QALY gained in older vs. younger patients was 
($99,720/QALYs gained vs. ($53,464/QALYs gained, P = 0.68).
CONCLUSION: ACDF surgery provided a significant gain in health-state utility in 
older patients with degenerative cervical pathology, with a mean cumulative 
2-year cost per QALY gained of $99,720/QALY. While older patients have a 
slightly higher cost utility compared to their younger counterparts, surgery in 
the older cohort does provide a significant improvement in pain, disability, and 
quality-of-life outcomes.

